<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-918-422  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 918 422.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 27 1989 v23 n48 p74(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A dial-up plan battens down the hatches. (Fiserv Inc'sdisaster-recovery scheme)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sehr, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiserv Inc has developed a disaster-recovery scheme based on ahigh-end modem and transmission of backup through dial-up lines.andO;The US Office of Regulatory Activities establishedcontingency-planning guidelines for financial institutions in Jul1989 to minimize financial loss and disruption of service.andP;  Thecompany handles record for over 19 million accounts at 800financial institutions, including banks, credit unions, andsavings and loans.andP;  Its data centers employ IBM, Unisys, and NCRmainframes.andP;  Dollar value was an important concern in selectingthe new system because of rapid obsolescence; flexibility was alsoa requirement because clients transmit data in different formats.andO;Fiserv selected an NEC Corp 9631 V.32 modem to place at eachclient site.andP;  Clients are given the option of a dial-up backupline, and a recovery center contains equipment able to support allcritical applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Fiserv Inc. (planning).andO;Ticker:    FISV.andO;Topic:     Back-Up SystemsDisaster PlanningDial-Up LinesData CommunicationsService Bureaus.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>